## Project - New
##
@node MenuNew "Menus: Project - New"
 Opens up a new empty editing window infront of the currently active window.
 This allows you to edit multiple files at once.  You can move from one
 editing window to another via the system depth gadgets, or using the @{i}Quill@{ui}
 commands @{" Next " link MenuNext}, @{" Previous " link MenuPrevious} or @{" Reveal " link MenuReveal}.

 There is currently a limit of 10 editor windows that can be open at any
 one time.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" NEW " link New}

@endnode

## Project - Clear
##
@node MenuClear "Menus: Project - Clear"
 Clears from memory the project in the current editor window, but will not
 touch the disk file.  If you have not saved that file since you last made a
 change to it, you will be given a chance to @{" save " link MenuSaveAs} it before the file is
 cleared.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" CLEAR " link Clear}
@endnode

## Project - Open
##
@node MenuOpen "Menus: Project - Open"
 Allows you to load a new text file into the current editor window.  If a file
 was already loaded into the current window, it will be replaced.  If you have
 not saved that file since you last made a change to it, you will be given a
 chance to @{" save " link MenuSaveAs} it before the new file is opened.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" OPEN " link Open}
@endnode

## Project - Insert
##
@node MenuInsert "Menus: Project - Insert"
 Lets you insert a file into the current project at the present cursor
 position.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" INSERT " link Insert}

@endnode

## Project - Save
##
@node MenuSave "Menus: Project - Save"
 Saves the file in the current editor window to disk, using the current project
 name.  If no name has been specified yet, you'll be able to select a name
 using the file requester.

 If a block is current being marked, then only the marked area will be
 saved.

 Be careful about overwriting an existing file, you will not be warned about
 this.

 If you wish to save the file under a name other than the current one, use the
 @{" Save As " link MenuSaveAs} command.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SAVE " link Save}

@endnode

## Project - Save As
##
@node MenuSaveAs "Menus: Project - Save As"
 Presents you with the file requester in order to select the name to save the
 file in the current window under.

 If a block is current being marked, then only the marked area will be
 saved.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SAVEAS " link SaveAs}

@endnode

## Project - Print
##
@node MenuPrint "Menus: Project - Print"
 Sends the file in the current editor window to the print "as-is".  Be sure 
 that you have your printer ready and setup as you want it to be via the
 Workbench Printer preferences.

 If a block is current being marked, then only the marked area will be
 printed.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" PRINT " link Print}

@endnode

## Project - Reveal - Next
##
@node MenuNext "Menus: Project - Reveal - Next"
 Takes you to the next open editor window, if you have more than one window
 open.  This works on a circular basic, if you do a next from the last
 editor window, you'll get the first window.

 This command is the opposite of the @{" Previous " link MenuPrevious} command.

 See also the @{" Reveal " link MenuReveal} command which allows you to select any of
 the open editor windows.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SELECT " link Select} NEXT

@endnode

## Project - Reveal - Previous
##
@node MenuPrevious "Menus: Project - Reveal - Previous"
 Takes you to the previous editor window, if you have more than one window
 open.  This works on a circular basic, if you do a previous from the first
 editor window, you'll get the last window.

 This command is the opposite of the @{" Next " link MenuNext} command.

 See also the @{" Reveal " link MenuReveal} command which allows you to select any of
 the open editor windows.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SELECT " link Select} PREVIOUS

@endnode

## Project - Reveal - Select
##
@node MenuReveal "Menus: Project - Reveal - Select"
 Presents you with a requester that allows you to select from any of the
 currently open editor windows.  Also displayed in this requester will the
 project's icon, as well as its length, etc.

 You can also use the @{" window depth gadgets " link Gadgets} to move from window to window,
 or the @{" Next " link MenuNext} and @{" Previous " link MenuPrevious} commands.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SELECT " link Select} PROMPT

@endnode

## Project - Close
##
@node MenuClose "Menus: Project - Close"
 Closes the current editor window.  If no other windows are currently open
 then a requester will appear prompting you to either @{" quit " link MenuQuit} or start a new
 untitled project.  If you have not saved that file since you last made a
 change to it, you will be given a chance to @{" save " link MenuSaveAs} it before the file is
 closed.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" CLOSE " link Close}

@endnode

## Project - About
##
@node MenuAbout "Menus: Project - About"
 Presents the copyright information about @{" Digital Quill " link AboutInfo}.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" ABOUT " link About}

@endnode

## Project - Iconify
##
@node MenuIconify "Menus: Project - Iconify"
 Closes down all editor windows and reduces to a simple icon on the
 Workbench.  Simply double-click on this icon and all windows will re-open
 into the same state they were before you selected Iconify.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" DEACTIVATE " link Deactivate}

@endnode

## Project - Quit
##
@node MenuQuit "Menus: Project - Quit"
 Exits @{i}Digital Quill@{ui} entirely.  If the project in any of the editor windows
 has not been saved since it was last modified, you will be given a chance to
 @{" save " link MenuSaveAs} them before quitting.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" QUIT " link Quit}

@endnode

## Edit - Mark
##
@node MenuMark "Menus: Edit - Mark"
 Puts the cursor into mark mode.  As you move the cursor, you will be
 highlighting text for such operations as @{" cut " link MenuCut} and @{" erase " link MenuErase}.  You can
 duplicate the action of this command by double-clicking the mouse, or
 simply dragging the mouse over the text, if @{" drag-marking " link MenuDragMarking} is on.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" MARK " link Mark}

@endnode

## Edit - Cut
##
@node MenuCut "Menus: Edit - Cut"
 Cuts the current @{" marked " link MenuMark} area.  The marked area is @{" copied " link MenuCopy} to the
 clipboard and then @{" erased " link MenuErase} from the window.  The standard system clipboard
 is used, so that the data cut can be pasted into other any editor window,
 as well as any other applications that are using the system clipboard.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" CUT " link Cut}

@endnode

## Edit - Copy
##
@node MenuCopy "Menus: Edit - Copy"
 Copies the @{" marked " link MenuMark} area to the clipboard.  The standard system clipboard is
 used, so that the data cut can be pasted into other any editor window, as
 well as any other applications that are using the system clipboard.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" COPY " link Copy}

@endnode

## Edit - Paste
##
@node MenuPaste "Menus: Edit - Paste"
 Takes the text from the standard system clipboard and inserts it into the
 current editor project at the current cursor position.  The data in the
 clipboard may have been @{" cut " link MenuCut} or @{" copied " link MenuCopy} from any @{i}Quill@{ui} editor window or
 any other application using the standard system clipboard.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" PASTE " link Paste}

@endnode

## Edit - Erase
##
@node MenuErase "Menus: Edit - Erase"
 Erases the currently @{" marked " link MenuMark} area.  If @{" drag-marking " link MenuDragMarking} is on, the same
 action can be done by pressing either the Erase or Delete.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" ERASE " link Erase}

@endnode

## Edit - Kill Line
##
@node MenuKillLine "Menus: Edit - Kill Line"
 Removes the entire contents of the current line in the current editor
 project including the newline.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" KILL " link Kill} LINE

@endnode

## Edit - Undo
##
@node MenuUndo "Menus: Edit - Undo"
 Reverses the last edit made.  Anything that changes the current project,
 entering text, deleting text, doing a @{" find and replace " link MenuReplace}, @{" pasting " link MenuPaste} from the
 clipboard, @{" erasing a block " link MenuErase}, etc. can all be undone.  You can undo for
 numerous levels, the limits of which are defined in the @{" Memory " link MenuMemory} requester.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" UNDO " link UnDo}

@endnode

## Edit - Redo
##
@node MenuRedo "Menus: Edit - Redo"
 If you have @{" undone " link MenuUndo} an edit and decide that you did not in fact want to
 undo it, you can redo that edit with this function.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" REDO " link ReDo}

@endnode

## Navigation - Find
##
@node MenuFind "Menus: Navigation - Find"
 Tries to find a string of text in the current editor project.  A requester
 will appear prompting you to enter the string of text you wish to find. 
 You also have the choice of setting the search as case sensitive, or using
 AmigaDOS pattern matching in the search.  The search will proceed from the
 current cursor position until the string has been found or the end of the
 project has been reached.  The search can be repeated by simply using the
 @{" Hunt " link MenuHunt} command.

 By default the search is case in-sensitive, that is, when looking for the
 string, upper and lowercase letters will be considered the same.  With the
 case sensitive option on, the string must match exactly.

 Optionally, pattern-matching can be used in the finds.  Pattern matching is
 powerful facility that will search for a string that matches a pattern
 description, rather than doing a simple equivalence check.  If you've used
 AmigaDOS pattern matching before (for example, "dir devs:#?.device", which
 the command to list all the files in devs: that end with the .device suffix)
 then you should be able to easily understand @{i}Quill's@{ui} pattern matching
 searches.  It does the same thing, supporting all the pattern matching
 symbols that AmigaDOS support (such as: #, ?, (), [], ~, `, etc.), searching
 from the current cursor position for text that matches the pattern you
 enter.  If you are not familiar with AmigaDOS pattern matching, consult your
 system manuals for a thorough description.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" FIND " link Find}

@endnode

## Navigation - Hunt
##
@node MenuHunt "Menus: Navigation - Hunt"
 Repeats that last @{" find " link MenuFind}.  If you haven't yet done a find, this command
 works exactly like the Find command, prompting you with the Find requester.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" FINDNEXT " link FindNext}

@endnode

## Navigation - Find & Replace
##
@node MenuReplace "Menus: Navigation - Find & Replace"
 Similar to the @{" Find " link MenuFind} command, except that it allows you to subsequently
 replace occurences of the string you're trying to find.

 The Find & Replace requester is very similar to the Find requester, except
 that it has some addition gadgets.  After entering the string to find, the
 next occurence of it (if any) will be searched for (starting from the
 current curor position).  You can then type in a string to possibly replace
 the string found with.  If you wish to replace it, click on the "Replace"
 gadget.  The old string will be deleted and the new one inserted, and the
 next occurence of the find string will be searched for.  If you don't want
 to replace that particular occurence, simply click on "Find Next" and no
 replace will be done, and the next occurence will be searched for.

 You also have the choice of automatically replacing every single occurence
 of the find string from the current cursor position on by clicking on the
 "Replace All" gadget.  Warning: this operation cannot be aborted, it should
 be used with care.

 Like with Find, you have the option of case sensitivity, and pattern
 matching.  Pattern matching generally is not suited to doing replaces, since
 the string actually found will vary and @{i}Quill@{ui} cannot know what exactly must
 be deleted before the replace string is inserted.  Only use pattern matching
 with replace if you really know what you're doing.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" FINDCHANGE " link FindChange} PROMPT

@endnode

## Navigation - Set Bookmark
##
@node MenuSetMark "Menus: Navigation - Set Bookmark"
 Places a bookmark at the current cursor position.  This means that the
 position of the bookmark will be remembered so that it can quickly be
 jumped to later with either @{" Goto Bookmark " link MenuGotoMark} or @{" Swap Bookmark " link MenuSwapMark}.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETBOOKMARK " link SetBookMark}

@endnode

## Navigation - Swap Bookmark
##
@node MenuSwapMark "Menus: Navigation - Swap Bookmark"
 Jumps to the @{" bookmark " link MenuSetMark}, making the old cursor position the new bookmark.
 This can be used to quickly toggle back and forth between two spots in a
 project.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SWAPBOOKMARK " link SwapBookMark}

@endnode

## Navigation - Go to Bookmark
##
@node MenuGotoMark "Menus: Navigation - Go to Bookmark"
 Jumps to the @{" bookmark " link SetBookMark}.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" GOTOBOOKMARK " link GotoBookMark}

@endnode

## Navigation - Jump to Line
##
@node MenuJump "Menus: Navigation - Jump to Line"
 Presents you with a requester asking for a line number to jump to.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" GOTOLINE " link GotoLine}

@endnode

## Navigation - Match Bracket
##
@node MenuMatchBracket "Menus: Navigation - Match Bracket"
 If the cursor is currently on a bracket, parenthesis, brace, or inequality
 sign, the matching symbol will be found and jumped to.  This facility fully
 handles nested brackets.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" MatchBracket " link MATCHBRACKET}

@endnode

## Format - Convert to Uppercase
##
@node MenuUppercase "Menus: Format - Convert to Uppercase"
 Converts from the cursor position to the end of the word to all uppercase
 letters, regardless of what case they were before.  Or, if an area is being
 @{" marked " link MenuMark}, that entire area will be converted to all uppercase.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" UPPERCASE " link UpperCase}

@endnode

## Format - Convert to Lowercase
##
@node MenuLowercase "Menus: Format - Convert to Lowercase"
 Converts from the cursor position to the end of the word to all lowercase
 letters, regardless of what case they were before.  Or, if an area is being
 @{" marked " link MenuMark}, that entire area will be converted to all lowercase.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" LOWERCASE " link LowerCase}

@endnode

## Format - Reformat Paragraph
##
@node MenuReformat "Menus: Format - Reformat Paragraph"
 Formats the current paragraph into @{" word-wrapped " link MenuWordWrap} lines that fit within the
 @{" right margin " link MenuRightMargin} setting.  @{i}Quill@{ui} has no hard definition of a paragraph, only
 of a line, so it will attempt to detect the end of the paragraph by looking
 for the following: two consecutive newlines, a newline followed by a space
 or tab, or the end of text.  This should be kept in mind when using this
 function or you might end up with unexpected results.  Reformat Paragraph
 generally only works well with words written in simple paragraph form with
 no extra spacing and indenting for formatting.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" REFORMAT " link Reformat}

@endnode

## Format - Centre Line
##
@node MenuCentre "Menus: Format - Centre Line"
 Centres the current line within the bounds of the @{" right margin " link MenuRightMargin}.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" CENTRE " link Centre}

@endnode

## Macros - Start Learning
##
@node MenuStartLearn "Menus: Macros - Start Learning"
 Starts learning a macro.  All actions between when you issue this command
 and @{" Stop Learning " link MenuStopLearn} will be remembered, and can be later @{" played-back " link MenuPlayback}.  The
 macro you learned can be subsequently saved to disk using the @{" Save Macro " link MenuSaveMacro}
 function.  The macro on disk can then be used via the @{" Execute " link MenuExecute} or
 @{" Assign Macro " link MenuAssignMacro} commands.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" LEARN " link Learn} 

@endnode

## Macros - Stop Learning
##
@node MenuStopLearn "Menus: Macros - Stop Learning"
 Stops learning the macro you started with @{" Start Learning " link MenuStartLearn}.  Now the macro
 can be @{" played back " link MenuPlayback} or @{" saved " link MenuSaveMacro} to disk.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" LEARN " link Learn} STOP

@endnode

## Macros - Playback
##
@node MenuPlayback "Menus: Macros - Playback"
 If a macro has been previously @{" learned " link MenuStartLearn} then it can be played back with
 this command.  This allows you to replay all actions between the start and
 end of learning.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" LEARN " link Learn} PLAY

@endnode

## Macros - Save Macro
##
@node MenuSaveMacro "Menus: Macros - Save Macro"
 If a macro has been previously @{" learned " link MenuStartLearn} then it can be saved to disk
 with this command.  Then this macro can be later used via the @{" Execute " link MenuExecute} or
 @{" Assign Macro " link MenuAssignMacro} commands.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" LEARN " link Learn} SAVE

@endnode

## Macros - Assign Macro
##
@node MenuAssignMacro "Menus: Macros - Assign Macro"
 This very powerful requester allows you to define macros of various types 
 for use throughout @{i}Quill@{ui}.  Macros are actions, or groups of actions. 
 Macros in @{i}Quill@{ui} allow you to automate just about every function in @{i}Quill@{ui}.
 Currently, the types of macros supported are:

  · Keystroke macros - Macros that are activated by pressing a key
    combination that you describe.

  · Menu Item macros - These are menu items that you define for the User
    pull-down menu that activate macros.

  · Speed Button - These are buttons in the SpeedBar (a line of buttons just
    below the window title bar) that invoke macros.

 You select what type of macro by pressing one of the buttons along the
 top of the Assign Macro requester.

 All types are defined in a similar way.  The gadgets for working on a
 macro are as follows:
 
  · Macros - Located at the left of the requester, this is a list of all
    the macros you've defined (if any).  If you want to view or edit the
    defition of a macro, just click on one of the items in this list.

  · New Macro - Creates a new macro.  Clicking this button creates a new
    blank macro for you to fill in the appropriate information.

  · Delete Macro - Deletes the macro that is currently selected.

  · Move Up - Moves the selected macro up one in the list.

  · Move Down - Moves the selected macro down one in the list.

  · Command for Macro - This is the most important part of each macro, it is
    the @{" command " link Commands} that the macro dispatches.  There are several ways
    to enter the command: Select from a list of all the @{i}Quill@{ui} commands, select
    a disk macro (i.e. an @{" ARexx macro " link ARexxInfo}), or select an
    AmigaDOS command to run.  Each of these will enter the appropriate
    command into the string gadget.  You can also type in the command
    itself into the string gadget, which will be the normal means of
    entering a command of any complexity.  Pressing the "?" button brings
    up help on the command you have chosen.

  · Key Combination (only displayed when defining Keystroke macros) -
    Keystroke macros need a key combination that invokes them, and you
    define that in here.  The keystroke descriptions are the same as
    Commodities hotkey descriptions, except that you are limited strictly to
    input that can be entered via the keyboard.  See your Amiga user manual
    for more information.

  · Menu Item Text (only displayed when defining Menu Item macros) - This
    is the text that will appear under the "User" pull-down menu for your
    macro.

  · Images (only displayed when defining SpeedButtons) - This is the list
    of images that you can choose for your SpeedButton.  Many images have
    default commands associated with them which will automatically be set
    when you select an image, if no command has already been defined. 
    This helps when setting up commonly used commands (like cut and
    paste).

  · Starts a New Group (only displayed when defining Menu Item macros and
    SpeedButtons) - For visual cleanliness, it is possible to group Menu
    Item macros and SpeedButtons by adding space between them (this wouldn't
    make any sense for Keystroke macros since you can't see them).  For Menu
    Item macros, this takes the form of a seperator bar in the menu, and for
    SpeedButtons it takes the form of an extra gap between buttons.

 Along the bottom are the standard buttons that appear in most requesters: 
 OK, Help and Cancel.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" ASSIGNMACRO " link AssignMacro}

@endnode

## Macros - Execute Macro
##
@node MenuExecuteMacro "Menus: Macros - ExecuteMacro"
 Executes a macro from disk.  Macros in @{i}Quill@{ui} are @{" ARexx " link ARexxInfo} macros, thus are
 generally found in the REXX: drawer and end in the .quill suffix.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" RX " link Rx}

@endnode

## Macros - Command Shell
##
@node MenuCommandShell "Menus: Macros - Command Shell"
 Opens up the command shell window.  This allows you to type any @{i}Quill@{ui}
 @{" command " link CmdIntro} and have it processed immediately.  Commands typed here actually
 get processed by @{" ARexx " link ARexxInfo} before they go through @{i}Quill's@{ui} command interpretor,
 thus you can use any ARexx command, contruct or function in the Command
 Shell.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" CMDSHELL " link CmdShell}

@endnode

## Settings - Print/Save Tabs?
##
@node MenuSaveTabs "Menus: Settings - Print/Save Tabs?"
 When this option is on, true tab characters (ASCII 9) will be preserved
 when printing and saving text.  Otherwise, tabs will be expanded into
 spaces.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT SAVETABS

@endnode

## Settings - Create Icons?
##
@node MenuCreateIcons "Menus: Settings - Create Icons?"
 If on, this option will cause insure that any file saved has an icon to
 go with it. @{i}Quill@{ui} will look in the ENV:Quill direcory and in the Icons
 directory within the directory Quill resides for different file types when
 the file being saved does not already have an icons.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT CREATEICONS

@endnode

## Settings - Display
##
@node MenuDisplay "Menus: Settings - Display"
 This requester is used to setup the @{i}Quill@{ui} display.  It allows you to
 select what screen or screen mode @{i}Quill@{ui} will use, the font for text, the
 screen's palette and the pens used for text.  The gadgets for controlling 
 these items are as follows:

  · Screen Type - There are three screen types that Quill can be run on:
    the Workbench screen, another application's public screen, or a custom
    public screen of Quill's own.

  · Select Screen - If you have chosen to run Quill on a public screen,
    this button brings up a list of all available public screens for you
    to select one.  If you are going to run Quill on a custom screen, this 
    button presents you with a list of available screen modes to choose
    from.  This button is disabled if you are have chosen to run Quill on
    the Workbench.

  · Select Text Font - This allows you to select which font to use for the 
    text in Quill's edit windows.  This font must be a monospaced
    (fixed-width) font, such as the Topaz font.

  · Screen Palette - These gadgets allow you to adjust the palette if Quill
    is running on a custom screen.

  · Text - The pen you wish to use for text in the Quill editing windows.

  · Background - The pen you wish to use for the background behind the
    text in Quill's edit windows.

 Along the bottom are the standard buttons that appear in most requesters: 
 OK, Help and Cancel.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" DISPLAY " link Display}

@endnode

## Settings - Memory
##
@node MenuMemory "Menus: Settings - Memory"
@{b}» FOR ADVANCED USERS ONLY@{ub}

 The Memory Settings requester allows you to modify how Quill manages
 memory.  This is intended strictly for advanced users, and in most cases
 you will not need to make any alterations.  If you do wish to make some
 changes, however, the gadgets available to you are as follows:

  · Initial Buffer Size - When a new project is created, this is the
    amount of space initially given to that project.  This space will grow 
    as needed and as memory permits.

  · Buffer Growth Increment - When the current amount of space allocated
    for the text buffer is exceeded, a new buffer will be allocated
    which will be the of kilobytes you select larger than the now full
    buffer.

  · Work Buffer Size - Specifies the size of the work buffer.  This is
    used for many things, amongst them, holding a temporary copy of the
    current line being edited.  This means that no line can be longer than 
    the size of the work buffer.

  · Clipboard Buffer Size - Clipboard operations use a buffer.  If you do
    large clips and are finding that they are being truncated, simply
    increase the amount of memory allocated for the clipboard buffer.

  · Clipboard Unit - Though the clipboard is global, there are actually
    255 different units of it, so that certain applications can share
    different clipboards and be excluded from others.  The "primary
    clipboard" is unit 0, which most Amiga applications make use of.

  · Undo Levels - This is the maximum amount of undo levels @{i}Quill@{ui} will
    keep.  You will not be able to go back farther than this number of
    steps.

  · Undo Memory - @{i}Quill@{ui} will not allow the memory used to keep track of
    undo steps to exceed this amount.  Global find & replaces take up the
    most memory to undo, so if you need to undo them often, you may wish
    to increase this.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" MEMORY " link Memory}

@endnode

## Settings - Backup Time...
##
@node MenuBackupTime "Menus: Settings - Backup Time..."
 Allows you to configure the time between automatic timed backups.  During
 a backup, all open projects will get saved as <filename>.backup.  This is
 to protect against accidental loss of data so that you will have a recent
 version of your file to revert so.

 Backup time is in minutes.  To disable timed backups altogether, enter a
 time of 0.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT BACKUPTIME

@endnode


## Settings - Editing - Insert Mode?
##
@node MenuInsertMode "Menus: Settings - Editing - Insert Mode?"
 When Insert Mode is on, typing in characters causes all characters under
 the cursor and beyond to be moved to the right to make a space for the
 new character.  When off, entering characters simply overwrites the
 characters that were there.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT EDITING INSERT

@endnode

## Settings - Editing - Word Wrap?
##
@node MenuWordWrap "Menus: Settings - Editing - Word Wrap?"
 The Word Wrap option gives simple word wrapping capabilities when
 entering text.  Once the end of a word is reached, if the cursor is beyond
 the right margin, that word will be moved to a new line automatically.
 This is the only time any checking for word wrapping will be done,
 paragraphs are not kept dynamically wrapped, you have to use
 @{" Reformat Paragraph " link MenuReformat} to make a paragraph properly word-wrapped.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT EDITING WORDWRAP

@endnode

## Settings - Editing - Auto-Indent?
##
@node MenuAutoIndent "Menus: Settings - Editing - Auto-Indent?"
 Auto-Indent is an option useful to programmers mostly.  When you press
 @{b}Return@{ub}, your new line will be given the same indentation as the previous
 line.  The indentation is the number of tabs or spaces before the first
 character or the cursor position (whichever comes first).

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT EDITING AUTOINDENT

@endnode

## Settings - Editing - False Tabs?
##
@node MenuFalseTabs "Menus: Settings - Editing - False Tabs?"
 When this option is on, pressing the @{b}Tab@{ub} key inserts the appropriate
 number of spaces, rather than a true tab character (ASCII 9).

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT EDITING FALSETABS

@endnode

## Settings - Editing - Tab Size
##
@node MenuTabSize "Menus: Settings - Editing - Tab Size"
 Specifies the tab size, in characters.  Valid sizes are from 1 to 10
 characters, with the default being 4.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT EDITING TABSIZE

@endnode

## Settings - Editing - Right Margin
##
@node MenuRightMargin "Menus: Settings - Editing - RightMargin"
 Specifies the right margin, to be used when @{" word wrapping " link MenuWordWrap},
 @{" reformating " link MenuReformat} and @{" centring " link MenuCentre}.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT EDITING MARGIN

@endnode

## Settings - Environment - Free Cursor?
##
@node MenuFreeCursor "Menus: Settings - Environment - Free Cursor?"
 Free Cursor mode allows the cursor to be positioned anywhere on a line,
 not bound by the line length.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT ENVIRONMENT FREECURSOR

@endnode

## Settings - Environment - Drag Marking?
##
@node MenuDragMarking "Menus: Settings - Environment - Drag Marking?"
 Drag Marking means to be able to @{" mark " link MenuMark} text simply by dragging the mouse,
 and not first having to select @{" mark " link MenuMark} mode via the menus or via
 double-clicking.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT ENVIRONMENT DRAGMARKING

@endnode

## Settings - Environment - Fence Posting?
##
@node MenuFencePosting "Menus: Settings - Environment - Fence Posting?"
 Toggles fence posting mode.  With fence posting on, whenever you enter a
 closing bracket, @{i}Quill@{ui} will jump to the opening bracket and flash the cursor
 over it for a moment, before restoring the cursor position.  This can be
 especially useful for ensuring complex bracketed expressions are entered
 correctly.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT ENVIRONMENT FENCEPOSTING

@endnode

## Settings - Environment - Show Hex?
##
@node MenuShowHex "Menus: Settings - Environment - Show Hex?"
 Toggles show hex mode.  With show hex on, the hexadecimal value of the
 character that the cursor is over will be shown in the window title bar.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT ENVIRONMENT SHOWHEX

@endnode

## Settings - Environment - SpeedBar Visible?
##
@node MenuSpeedBar "Menus: Settings - Environment - SpeedBar Visible?"
 If you have configured a SpeedBar, you can make them visible or invisible.
 If you have configured SpeedButtons and are finding that your SpeedBar is
 not showing up, check to make sure this option is on.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT ENVIRONMENT SPEEDBAR

@endnode

## Settings - Environment - Large SpeedButtons?
##
@node MenuLargeButtons "Menus: Settings - Environment - Large SpeedButtons?"
 If you have configured a SpeedBar, you can toggle them between the normal
 size and the larger size.  For the larger size to work, the file
 "SpeedButtons.8" must be in Quill's directory.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SETTATTR " link SetAttr} PROJECT ENVIRONMENT LARGEBUTTONS

@endnode

## Settings - Load Settings
##
@node MenuLoadSettings "Menus: Settings - Load Settings"
 Allows you to load a settings file from disk using the file requester. 
 Some settings affect all projects (text font, colours) while others only
 affect the current project.

 The settings consist of all parameters set via the @{" Settings " link Menus} pull-down
 menu, and in addition: the current window position and size, the current
 directory, the current file requester pattern, etc.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" LOADSETTINGS " link LoadSettings}

@endnode

## Settings - Save Settings
##
@node MenuSaveSettings "Menus: Settings - Save Settings"
 Saves the Digital Quill settings to disk.

 The settings consist of all parameters set via the @{" Settings " link Menus} pull-down
 menu, and in addition: the current window position and size, the current
 directory, the current file requester pattern, etc.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SAVESETTINGS " link SaveSettings}

@endnode

## Settings - Save Settings As
##
@node MenuSaveSettingsAs "Menus: Settings - Save Settings As"
 Presents you with the file requester to select a file to save the @{i}Digital
 Quill@{ui} settings to.

 The settings consist of all parameters set via the @{" Settings " link Menus} pull-down
 menu, and in addition: the current window position and size, the current
 directory, the current file requester pattern, etc.

 @{b}Command reference:@{ub} @{" SAVESETTINGSAS " link SaveSettingsAs}

@endnode


## Main window gadgets
##
@node Window "Editing Window"
 @{i}Digital Quill@{ui} loads text into standard Amiga Intuition windows that you
 will be very familiar with.  Around the border of it, you see the standard
 close gadget on the top left, which is synonymous to the @{" CLOSE " link Close} command.
 Over to the right is the zip gadget and the depth gadget, and down the right
 hand-side of the windows you'll see a  scrollbar and arrows, with the
 standard sizing gadget just below that. 

 Also in the window border is some status information.  Next to the close
 gadget on the top left is given the number of the project window you've
 got open, as well as the filename of the project being worked on.  Over to
 the right is the modes of the window, this looks something like:

     I·w·A·t·C·D·f·S

Each letter represents a mode item, and it is capitalized when the item is 
on and in lower  case when it is off.  Each letter corresponds to the
following:

     I - @{" Insert mode " link MenuInsertMode}
     W - @{" Word wrap " link MenuWordWrap}
     A - @{" Auto-indent " link MenuAutoIndent}
     T - @{" False tabs " link MenuFalseTabs}
     C - @{" Free Cursor " link MenuFreeCursor}
     D - @{" Drag marking " link MenuDragMarking}
     F - @{" Fence posting " link MenuFencePosting}
     S - @{" Save/print tabs " link MenuSaveTabs}

 In the above example, that modes would be insert mode on, word wrap off,
 auto-indent on, false tabs off (use real tabs), free cursor on, drag
 marking on, fence posting on, and save/print tabs on.

 If you have the @{" Show Hex " link MenuShowHex} option on, then just to the right of the modes
 will be the hexadecimal ASCII value of the character you're over.  And
 just to the right of that you are shown the current Line and Column that
 the cursor is on in your project.

@endnode


## Keyboard Controls
##
@node KeyboardControls "Keyboard Controls"
 Most keystrokes you enter will go directly into the text of the currently
 active editor window.  @{i}Quill@{ui} recognizes your current keymap settings,
 and will allow you to enter high-bit characters, "dead-key" sequences, etc.

 In addition, @{i}Quill@{ui} has several special keystrokes that it recognizes:

   @{b}Return@{ub}
     Splits the current line into two at the current cursor position.  If
     @{" Auto-Indent " link MenuAutoIndent} is on, the new line will be indented in the same way as
     the line you were just on.
   @{b}Shift-Return@{ub}
     Same as above, except the the compliment of Auto-Indent is looked at.
     i.e. if @{" Auto-Indent " link MenuAutoIndent} is on, the line will not be indented, but will be
     if it is off.
   @{b}Enter@{ub}
     Same as @{b}Shift-Return@{ub}.
   @{b}Shift-Enter@{ub}
     Same as @{b}Return@{ub}.
   @{b}CursorUp / CursorDown@{ub}
     Moves the cursor up or down one line.  If the cursor is at the upper
     or lower extreme of the screen, the text will scroll, unless you are
     at the appropriate extreme of the project.
   @{b}Shift-CursorUp / Shift-CursorDown@{ub}
     Moves the cursor to the upper or lower extreme of the screen.  If the
     cursor is already at the appropriate extreme of the screen, the text
     will scroll up or down one screenful of text.
   @{b}Ctrl-CursorUp / Ctrl-CursorDown@{ub}
     Moves the cursor to the top or bottom of the current project.
   @{b}Alt-CursorUp / Alt-CursorDown@{ub}
     Same as above.
   @{b}CursorLeft / CursorRight@{ub}
     Moves the cursor left or right one character.  If the cursor is at the
     start of the line and you try to move left, it will go up to the end
     of the previous line.
   @{b}Shift-CursorLeft / Shift-CursorRight@{ub}
     Moves the cursor to the left or right extreme of the screen.  If the
     cursor is already at this extreme, the screen will be scrolled left or
     right one screenful, until you're at the start or finish of the line.
   @{b}Ctrl-CursorLeft / Ctrl-CursorRight@{ub}
     Moves the cursor to the extreme left or right of the current line.
   @{b}Alt-CursorLeft / Alt-CursorRight@{ub}
     Moves the cursor to the start/end of the previous or next word.
   @{b}Backspace@{ub}
     Deletes the character to the immediate left of the cursor.  If the
     cursor is on the first character on a line, then the current line will
     be joined with the previous line.  If @{" drag-marking " link MenuDragMarking} is on, it will
     @{" erase " link MenuErase} the currently @{" marked " link MenuMark} area if you were marking.
   @{b}Delete@{ub}
     Deletes the character currently under the cursor (if there is one).  If
     @{" drag-marking " link MenuDragMarking} is on, it will @{" erase " link MenuErase} the currently @{" marked " link MenuMark} area if
     you were marking.
   @{b}Shift-Backspace@{ub}
     Deletes all characters from the cursor position to the beginning of
     the current line.
   @{b}Shift-Delete@{ub}
     Deletes all characters from the cursor position to the end of the
     current line.
   @{b}Ctrl-Backspace@{ub}
     Deletes all characters from the cursor position to the beginning of
     the current word.
   @{b}Ctrl-Delete@{ub}
     Deletes all characters from the cursor position to the end of the
     current word.
   @{b}Help@{ub}
     Takes you into @{i}Quill@{ui}'s interactive hypertext AmigaGuide® @{" help " link UsingHelp}
     system (which is what you're using right now).  Help can be accessed
     while in any editing window or requester and will provide context-
     sensitive aid. You can also press the @{b}Help@{ub} key while the mouse is over a
     pull-down menu item for information about that.

 Do not forget that additional keystrokes can be configured to do whatever
 you want via the Assign Macro requester.

 @{i}Quill@{ui}'s requesters also provide extensive keyboard controls.  You will
 notice that the labels for most gadget labels have a letter underlined. 
 This is the key you use to access that gadget.  In the case of cycle
 gadgets or listview gadgets, you can hold down @{b}Shift@{ub} and press the key
 equivalent to move backwards through the list, while unshifted moves you
 forwards through the list.  In all requesters (with the exception of the
 system requesters for selecting files, fonts and screenmodes) you can
 press @{b}Return@{ub} as an a equivalent to selecting "OK" and @{b}Escape@{ub} as an
 equivalent to selecting "Cancel".

@endnode


