## Commmand Language Intro
##
@node CmdIntro "Introduction to the command language"
 The inner workings of @{i}Digital Quill@{ui} are based around its internal command
 language.  Most of the time, this language is hidden from you, but every
 gadget click, menu-selection, and even macros you record, go through this
 language.  @{i}Quill@{ui} is thus known as a "command-driven" application.

 Because the processing of its commands is fundamental to the operation of
 @{i}Quill@{ui}, understanding its command set will help you to better use the
 programme.  As a user, you access the command set directly when using
 macros in @{i}Quill@{ui}, its command shell, as well as via its @{" ARexx " link ARexxInfo} interface.
 And, as mentioned above, you access it indirectly when doing just about
 anything else.

 In the command reference section, all commands are described in three ways,
 usage, template, and a general description.

  · The @{i}usage@{ui} shows what you would type to use the command.  Parts that are
    optional are enclosed in brackets [].  Parts where you must enter some
    kind of information are enclosed in inequality signs <>.  Finally, to
    indicate a choice the items to choose from will be seperated by a pipe |.
  · The @{i}template@{ui} is a standarda AmigaDOS template and this is the actual
    argument template used to parse the command arguments.  See your Amiga
    system manual for a description of AmigaDOS templates.
  · The @{i}general description@{ui} provides details on using the command and on what
    the various options do.  Note that many commands return values.  If you
    are using ARexx, the values will be returned in the variable RESULT.  If
    there was an error with the command, the variable RC will contain the
    value 5.
   

@endnode

## Commmand Language Intro
##
@node ARexxInfo "Quill and ARexx"
 ARexx is the Amiga's macro processing scripting language, it was included
 with your system.  ARexx is very simple yet extremely powerful, allowing to
 very easily and quickly create programmes.  What makes it unique and
 extraordinarily powerful is its ability to communicate with any application
 that has an ARexx port.

 @{i}Quill@{ui} makes good use of this power.  Via its ARexx port, ARexx macros can
 access any of @{i}Quill's@{ui} @{" commands " link CmdIntro}.  This allows you to automate virtually any
 kind of edit action, and allows you to extend @{i}Quill@{ui} virtually as far as your
 ability and imagination will let you.

 Macros @{" learned " link MenuStartLean} within @{i}Quill@{ui} are actually ARexx macros and are @{" played back " link MenuPlayback}
 by running them through the ARexx interpretor.  When you @{" execute " link MenuExecute} a macro
 you are starting an ARexx macro.  @{i}Quill@{ui}'s ARexx port is a direct link for
 any outside applications to @{i}Quill's@{ui} extensive command set.

@endnode

## ABOUT
##
@node About "Command Reference: ABOUT"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} ABOUT
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Presents the copyright information about @{" Digital Quill " link AboutInfo} in a
 requester.

@endnode

## ACTIVATE
##
@node Activate "Command Reference: ACTIVATE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} ACTIVATE
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Brings the @{i}Quill@{ui} screen to the front and makes the current project window
 (the one that was last active) the currently active window.  If @{i}Quill@{ui} was
 @{" iconified " link Deactivate} then it will be de-iconified first.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Deactivate} DEACTIVATE

@endnode

## ASSIGNMACRO
##
@node AssignMacro "Command Reference: ASSIGNMACRO"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} ASSIGNMACRO
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Presents the @{" Assign Macro " link MenuAssignMacro} requester for configuring macros in @{i}Quill@{ui}.

@endnode

## BACKGROUNDPEN
##
@node BackgroundPen "Command Reference: BACKGROUNDPEN"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} BACKGROUNDPEN @{i}<pen number>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} /N

 Changes the colour of the background pen in all project windows to the given
 pen number.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link TextPen} TEXTPEN

@endnode

## BEEPSCREEN
##
@node BeepScreen "Command Reference: BEEPSCREEN"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} BEEPSCREEN
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Flashes and/or beeps the Quill screen (depending on the user's system
 settings.

@endnode

## CHANGEWINDOW
##
@node ChangeWindow "Command Reference: CHANGEWINDOW"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} CHANGEWINDOW [LEFTEDGE] @{i}<left edge>@{ui} [TOPEDGE] @{i}<top edge>@{ui}
                 [WIDTH] @{i}<width>@{ui} [HEIGHT] @{i}<height>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} LEFTEDGE/N,TOPEDGE/N,WIDTH/N,HEIGHT/N

 Moves and sizes the current project window in one operation.

  · LEFTEDGE is the new left edge you want.

  · TOPEDGE is the new top edge you want.

  · WIDTH is the new width you want.

  · HEIGHT is the new height you want.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link MoveWindow} MOVEWINDOW
   @{"  " link SizeWindow} SIZEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ZoomWindow} ZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link UnZoomWindow} UNZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link WindowToFront} WINDOWTOFRONT
   @{"  " link WindowToBack} WINDOWTOBACK
   @{"  " link ScreenToFront} SCREENTOFRONT
   @{"  " link ScreenToBack} SCREENTOBACK

@endnode

## CENTRE
##
@node Centre "Command Reference: CENTRE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} CENTRE
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Centres the current line within the bounds of the @{" right margin " link SetAttr}.

@endnode

## CLEAR
##
@node Clear "Command Reference: CLEAR"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} CLEAR [FORCE]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FORCE/S

 Clears from memory the project in the current editor window, but will not
 touch the disk file.  If you have not saved that file since you last made a
 change to it, you will be given a chance to @{" save " link SaveAs} it before the project
 is cleared

  · FORCE suppresses the Modified Project requester.

@endnode

## CLOSE
##
@node Close "Command Reference: CLOSE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} CLOSE [FORCE]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FORCE/S

 Closes the current editor window.  If that was the only open window, @{i}Quill@{ui}
 will prompt you to either exit completely or start a new untitled project. 
 Otherwise, the next window will become the current one.

  · FORCE suppresses the Modified Project requester.

@endnode

## CMDSHELL
##
@node CmdShell "Command Reference: CMDSHELL"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} CMDSHELL
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Opens up the interactive @{" ARexx " link ARexxInfo} command shell.

@endnode

## COLUMN
##
@node Column "Command Reference: COLUMN"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} COLUMN @{i}<displacement>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} /N/A

 Moves the cursor left or right relative to the current cursor position.
 Passing a negative value moves the cursor left, a positive value moves the
 cursor right.  The screen will automatically scroll as appropriate.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GotoLine} GOTOLINE
   @{"  " link GotoColumn} GOTOCOLUMN
   @{"  " link Cursor} CURSOR
   @{"  " link Line} LINE
   @{"  " link NextWord} NEXTWORD
   @{"  " link PreviousWord} PREVIOUSWORD
   @{"  " link Position} POSITION

@endnode

## COPY
##
@node Copy "Command Reference: COPY"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} COPY
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Copies the @{" marked " link Mark} area to the clipboard.  The standard system clipboard is
 used, so that the data cut can be pasted into other any editor window, as
 well as any other applications that are using the system clipboard.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Mark} MARK
   @{"  " link Cut} CUT
   @{"  " link Paste} PASTE
   @{"  " link Erase} ERASE

@endnode

## CR
##
@node CR "Command Reference: CR"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} CR [INDENT]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} INDENT/S

 Splits the current line into two at the current cursor position.

  · INDENT means that the line should be indented to match the indent of the
    previous line.

@endnode

## CURSOR
##
@node Cursor "Command Reference: CURSOR"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} CURSOR UP | DOWN | LEFT | RIGHT
 @{b}Template:@{ub} UP/S,DOWN/S,LEFT/S,RIGHT/S

 Moves the cursor up, down, left or right a single line or column.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GotoLine} GOTOLINE
   @{"  " link GotoColumn} GOTOCOLUMN
   @{"  " link Line} LINE
   @{"  " link Column} COLUMN
   @{"  " link NextWord} NEXTWORD
   @{"  " link PreviousWord} PREVIOUSWORD
   @{"  " link Position} POSITION

@endnode

## CUT
##
@node Cut "Command Reference: CUT"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} CUT
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Cuts the current @{" marked " link Mark} area.  The marked area is @{" copied " link Copy} to the
 clipboard and then @{" erased " link Erase}.  The standard system clipboard is used, so that
 the data cut can be pasted into other any editor window, as well as any
 other applications that are using the system clipboard.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Mark} MARK
   @{"  " link Copy} COPY
   @{"  " link Paste} PASTE
   @{"  " link Erase} ERASE

@endnode

## DEACTIVATE
##
@node Deactivate "Command Reference: DEACTIVATE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} DEACTIVATE
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Closes down all editor windows and reduces Quill to a simple icon on the
 Workbench.  Simply double-click on this icon or use the @{" ACTIVATE " link Activate} command
 and all windows will re-open into the same state they were before you
 used the DEACTIVATE command.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Activate} ACTIVATE

@endnode

## DELETECHAR
##
@node DeleteChar "Command Reference: DELETECHAR"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} DELETECHAR
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Deletes the character currently under the cursor (if there is one).  If
 @{" drag-marking " link SetAttr} is on, it will @{" erase " link Erase} the currently @{" marked " link Mark} area if
 you were marking.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link EraseChar} ERASECHAR

@endnode

## DISPLAY
##
@node Display "Command Reference: DISPLAY"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} DISPLAY
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Presents the @{" Display " link MenuDisplay} requester for configuring the @{i}Quill@{ui} display.

@endnode

## ERASE
##
@node Erase "Command Reference: ERASE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} ERASE [FORCE]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FORCE/S

 Erases the currently @{" marked " link MenuMark} area.

  · FORCE supresses the "Are you sure?" requester.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Mark} MARK
   @{"  " link Cut} CUT
   @{"  " link Copy} COPY
   @{"  " link Paste} PASTE

@endnode

## ERASECHAR
##
@node EraseChar "Command Reference: ERASECHAR"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} ERASECHAR
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Deletes the character to the immediate left of the cursor.  If the cursor
 is on the first character on a line, then the current line will be joined
 with the previous line.  If @{" drag-marking " link SetAttr} is on, it will @{" erase " link Erase} the
 currently @{" marked " link Mark} area if you were marking.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link DeleteChar} DELETECHAR

@endnode

## FIND
##
@node Find "Command Reference: FIND"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} FIND [[TEXT] @{i}<text>@{ui}]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} TEXT/F

 Tries to find a string of text in the current editor project.  If the TEXT 
 parameter is not specified, a requester will appear prompting you to enter
 the string of text to find.  You also have the choice of setting the search
 as case sensitive, or using AmigaDOS pattern matching in the search.  The
 search will proceed from the current cursor position until the string has
 been found or the end of the project has been reached.  The search can be
 repeated without having to use the Find requester again by using the
 @{" FINDNEXT " link FindNext} command.

 By default the search is case in-sensitive, that is, when looking for the
 string, upper and lowercase letters will be considered the same.  With the
 case sensitive option on, the string must match exactly.

 Optionally, pattern-matching can be used in the finds.  Pattern matching is
 powerful facility that will search for a string that matches a pattern
 description, rather than doing a simple equivalence check.  If you've used
 AmigaDOS pattern matching before (for example, "dir devs:#?.device", which
 the command to list all the files in devs: that end with the .device suffix)
 then you should be able to easily understand @{i}Quill's@{ui} pattern matching
 searches.  It does the same thing, supporting all the pattern matching
 symbols that AmigaDOS support (such as: #, ?, (), [], ~, `, etc.), searching
 from the current cursor position for text that matches the pattern you
 enter.  If you are not familiar with AmigaDOS pattern matching, consult your
 system manuals for a thorough description.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link FindNext} FINDNEXT
   @{"  " link FindChange} FINDCHANGE

@endnode

## FINDCHANGE
##
@node FindChange "Command Reference: FINDCHANGE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} FINDCHANGE [ALL] [PROMPT] [FIND @{i}<string1>@{ui}] [CHANGE @{i}<string2>@{ui}]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ALL/S,PROMPT/S,FIND/K,CHANGE/K

 Presents the @{" Find & Replace " link MenuReplace} requester.

  · FIND specifies the string to find.

  · CHANGE specifies the string to replace.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Find} FIND
   @{"  " link FindNext} FINDNEXT

@endnode

## FINDNEXT
##
@node FindNext "Command Reference: FINDNEXT"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} FINDNTEXT
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Moves the cursor to the next occurence of the current find string.  If there
 currently is no find string, the @{" Find requester " link MenuFind} will be displayed.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Find} FIND
   @{"  " link FindChange} FINDCHANGE

@endnode

## GETATTR
##
@node GetAttr "Command Reference: GETATTR"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} GETATTR [OBJECT] @{i}<object>@{ui} [[FIELD1] @{i}<field1>@{ui}] [[FIELD2] @{i}<field2>@{ui}]
        [[STEM] @{i}<stem>@{ui}] [[VAR] @{i}<var>@{ui}]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} OBJECT/A,FIELD1,FIELD2,STEM/K,VAR/K

 This command allows you to query information from @{i}Quill@{ui}.  Attributes are
 hierachical, you can fetch one specific attribute into RESULT or a variable
 given by the @{i}VAR@{ui} argument, or you get a group into a stem variable given by
 the @{i}STEM@{ui} argument.

  · OBJECT can be used to get attributes from any of the following:
     · APPLICATION  - @{i}See fields for the APPLICATION object below.@{ui}
     · PROJECT      - @{i}See fields for the PROJECT object below.@{ui}
     · WINDOW       - @{i}See fields for the WINDOW object below.@{ui}
     · PROJECTS     - @{i}See special notes on using the PROJECTS and@{ui}
     · WINDOWS        @{i}WINDOWS objects below.@{ui}

    The PROJECTS and WINDOWS objects are special.  They copy the PROJECT and
    WINDOW atttributes of all currently open projects into a stem variable.
    @{i}<stemname>@{ui}.COUNT will contain the number of projects, @{i}<stemname>@{ui}.@{i}<#>@{ui} will
    contain the info for each open project, from 0 to n.

  · FIELD1 allows you to get a field of information from an @{i}object@{ui}.

    With the APPLICATION object, @{i}field1@{ui} can be used to get the following
    attributes:
     · VERSION      - Current version of @{i}Digital Quill@{ui}.
     · SCREEN       - The name of the public screen @{i}Quill@{ui} is running on.
     · ICONIFIED    - Whether or not @{i}Quill@{ui} is iconified.

    With the PROJECT object, @{i}field1@{ui} can be used to get the following
    attributes:
     · AREXX          - Name of the ARexx port used by the project.
     · NUMBER         - Number of the project's window.
     · FILENAME       - Complete filename of the project.
     · PATH           - Directory (path) the project resides in.
     · FILE           - Name of project.
     · PRIORITY       - The task priority that @{i}Quill@{ui} is running at.
     · CHANGED        - If the current project has been changed since last
                        saved.
     · LENGTH         - Size of the current project in bytes.
     · LINES          - Number of lines of the current project.
     · POS            - Byte offset of the cursor from the start of the current
                        project.
     · BOOKMARK       - The line of the bookmark in the current project.
     · LINE           - Line that the cursor is currently on.
     · LINELENGTH     - Length of the current line.
     · MARKINGBLOCK   - If a block is currently being marked.
     · BLOCKSTARTPOS  - Byte position of the start of the block.
     · BLOCKSTARTCOL  - Column the block starts in.
     · BLOCKSTARTLINE - Line the block starts on.
     · BLOCKENDPOS    - Byte position of the end of the block.
     · BLOCKENDCOL    - Column the block ends in.
     · BLOCKENDLINE   - Line the block ends on.
     · COLUMN         - Column that the cursor is currently in.
     · BACKUPTIME     - Number of minutes between @{" timed backups " link MenuBackupTime}.
     · SAVETABS       - State of the @{" Save Tabs " link MenuSaveTabs} option.
     · CREATEICONS    - State of the @{" Create Icons " link MenuCreateIcons} option.
     · EDITING        - @{i}See sub-fields for EDITING below.@{ui}
     · ENVIRONMENT    - @{i}See sub-fields for ENVIRONEMENT below.@{ui}

    With the WINDOW object, @{i}field1@{ui} can be used to get the following
    attributes:
     · TOP            - Position of the top edge of the current project window.
     · LEFT           - Position of the left edge of the current project
                        window.
     · WIDTH          - Width of the current project window.
     · HEIGHT         - Height of the current project window.

  · FIELD2 allows you to get a more specific field of information from a
    @{i}field@{ui} within an @{i}object@{ui}.

    From the field1 EDITING in the PROJECT object, the sub-field @{i}field2@{ui} can
    be any of:
     · INSERT         - State of the @{" Insert Mode " link MenuInsertMode} option.
     · WORDWRAP       - State of the @{" Word Wrap " link MenuWordWrap} option.
     · AUTOINDENT     - State of the @{" Auto-Indent " link MenuAutoIndent} option.
     · FALSETABS      - State of the @{" False Tabs " link MenuFalseTabs} option.
     · TABSIZE        - Current @{" tab size " link MenuTabSize}.
     · RIGHTMARGIN    - Current @{" right margin " link MenuRightMargin}.

    From the field1 ENVIRONMENT in the PROJECT object, the sub-field @{i}field2@{ui}
    can be any of:
     · FREECURSOR   - State of the @{" Free Cursor " link MenuFreeCursor} option.
     · DRAGMARK     - State of the @{" Drag Marking " link MenuDragMarking} option.
     · FENCEPOSTING - State of the @{" Fence Posting " link MenuFencePosting} option.
     · SHOWHEX      - State of the @{" Show Hex " link MenuShowHex} option.
     · SPEEDBAR     - State of the @{" SpeedBar Visible " link MenuSpeedBar} option.
     · LARGEBUTTONS - State of the @{" Large SpeedButtons " link MenuLargeButtons} option.

 @{b}Examples:@{ub}
   To get the filename of the current project into the ARexx RESULT variable:
     GETATTR PROJECT FILENAME

   To get the public screen name of @{i}Quill@{ui} and put it into the pubscreen ARexx
   variable:
     GETATTR APPLICATION SCREEN VAR pubscreen

   To get the window information of the current project and place it into the
   ARexx stem variable window_attrs:
     GETATTR WINDOW STEM window_attrs
   window_attrs.top will have the window's top edge, window_attrs.left will
   have its left edge, etc.

   To get the window information on all open projects and place it into the
   ARexx stem variable windows_attrs:
     GETATTR WINDOW STEM windows_attrs
   In this case, windows_attrs.0.top will have the top edge of the first
   project, windows_attrs.0.top will the top edge of the second project, etc.

   To get the project information on all currently open projects and place the
   info in the ARexx stem variable projects_info:
     GETATTR PROJECTS STEM projects_info
   projects_info.count will contain the number of open projects.
   projects_info.0.filename will contain the filename of the first project
   found, projects_info.1.filename will contain the filename of the second
   project found, etc.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link SetAttr} SETATTR

@endnode

## GETCHAR
##
@node GetChar "Command Reference: GETCHAR"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} GETCHAR
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Returns the character that the cursor is currently over.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GetWord} GETWORD
   @{"  " link GetLine} GETLINE

@endnode

## GETLINE
##
@node GetLine "Command Reference: GETLINE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} GETLINE
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Returns the entire contents of the line that the cursor is currently on.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GetChar} GETCHAR
   @{"  " link GetWord} GETWORD

@endnode

## GETWORD
##
@node GetWord "Command Reference: GETWORD"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} GETWORD
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Returns the word that the cursor is currently over in RESULT, or an error
 level of 5 in RC if the cursor is not on a word.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GetChar} GETCHAR
   @{"  " link GetLine} GETLINE

@endnode

## GOTOBOOKMARK
##
@node GotoBookMark "Command Reference: GOTOBOOKMARK"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} GOTOBOOKMARK
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Jumps to the @{" bookmark " link MenuSetMark}.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link SetBookMark} SETBOOKMARK
   @{"  " link SwapBookMark} SWAPBOOKMARK

@endnode

## GOTOCOLUMN
##
@node GotoColumn "Command Reference: GOTOCOLUMN"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} GOTOCOLUMN @{i}<column>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} /N/A

 Moves the cursor to a specified column on the current line.

 Note that this command does not look at expanded tabs, a tab will always
 be regarded as one column.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GotoLine} GOTOLINE
   @{"  " link Cursor} CURSOR
   @{"  " link Line} LINE
   @{"  " link Column} COLUMN
   @{"  " link NextWord} NEXTWORD
   @{"  " link PreviousWord} PREVIOUSWORD
   @{"  " link Position} POSITION

@endnode

## GOTOLINE
##
@node GotoLine "Command Reference: GOTOLINE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} GOTOLINE [@{i}<line>@{ui}]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} /N

 Moves the cursor to a specified line, keeping the current column.  If no
 line is specified, the user will be prompted to enter a line number.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GotoColumn} GOTOCOLUMN
   @{"  " link Cursor} CURSOR
   @{"  " link Line} LINE
   @{"  " link Column} COLUMN
   @{"  " link NextWord} NEXTWORD
   @{"  " link PreviousWord} PREVIOUSWORD
   @{"  " link Position} POSITION

@endnode

## HELP
##
@node Help "Command Reference: HELP"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} HELP [[COMMAND] @{i}<command>@{ui}] [PROMPT]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} COMMAND,PROMPT/S

 Provides you with online help information about @{i}Quill@{ui}.

  · COMMAND presents you with a list of options available for that command.
  · PROMPT activates the graphical hypertext help system.

@endnode

## INSERT
##
@node Insert "Command Reference: INSERT"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} INSERT [[FILENAME] @{i}<filename>@{ui}]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FILENAME

 Opens the specified file and inserts it at the current cursor position in
 the current editor window.  If no filename is passed, the user will
 be presented with the file requester for selecting a file.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Open} OPEN

@endnode

## KILL
##
@node Kill "Command Reference: KILL"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} KILL LINE | EOL | SOL
 @{b}Template:@{ub} LINE/S,EOL/S,SOL/S

 Removes text in one of a variety of manners.

  · LINE causes the entire line to be removed.

  · EOL kills all text from the cursor to the end of line.

  · SOL kills all text from the cursor to the start of line.

@endnode

## LEARN
##
@node Learn "Command Reference: LEARN"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} LEARN FILE @{i}<filename>@{ui} | STOP | PLAY | SAVE
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FILE/K,STOP/S,PLAY/S,SAVE/S

 Controls Quill's macro learning.  With no parameters, causes Quill to
 start learning a macro.  All actions between when you issue this command
 and LEARN STOP will be remembered, and can be later played-back with LEARN
 PLAY.  The macro you learned can be subsequently saved to disk using
 LEARN SAVE.  The macro on disk can then be used via the @{" RX " link Rx} or
 @{" Assign Macro " link AssignMacro} commands.

  · FILENAME specifies a filename to directly learn the macro to, rather
    that having to specify LEARN SAVE.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link RX} RX

@endnode

## LINE
##
@node Line "Command Reference: LINE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} LINE @{i}<displacement>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} /N/A

 Moves the cursor up or down relative to the current cursor position.
 Passing a negative value moves the cursor up, a positive value moves the
 cursor down.  The screen will automatically scroll as appropriate.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GotoLine} GOTOLINE
   @{"  " link GotoColumn} GOTOCOLUMN
   @{"  " link Cursor} CURSOR
   @{"  " link Column} COLUMN
   @{"  " link NextWord} NEXTWORD
   @{"  " link PreviousWord} PREVIOUSWORD
   @{"  " link Position} POSITION

@endnode

## LOADSETTINGS
##
@node LoadSettings "Command Reference: LOADSETTINGS"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} LOADSETTINGS [[FILENAME] @{i}<filename>@{ui}]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FILENAME

 Load a @{i}Digital Quill@{ui} settings file.  If no file is specified, the user
 will be presented with the file requester for selecting a file.

 The settings consist of all parameters set via the @{" Settings " link Menus} pull-down
 menu, and in addition: the current window position and size, the current
 directory, the current file requester pattern, etc.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link SaveSettings} SAVESETTINGS
   @{"  " link SaveSettingsAs} SAVESETTINGSAS

@endnode

## LOCKGUI
##
@node LockGUI "Command Reference: LOCKGUI"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} LOCKGUI
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Locks user input to @{i}Quill@{ui} graphic user interface.  The pointer will change
 to the busy pointer and the user will not be able to use the mouse for any
 operations.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link UnlockGUI} UNLOCKGUI

@endnode

## LOWERCASE
##
@node LowerCase "Command Reference: LOWERCASE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} LOWERCASE
 @{b}Template:@{ub} CHAR/S,WORD/S,LINE/S

 Converts from the cursor position to the end of the word to all lowercase
 letters, regardless of what case they were before.  Or, if an area is being
 @{" marked " link Mark}, that entire area will be converted to all lowercase.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link UpperCase} UPPERCASE

@endnode

## MARK
##
@node Mark "Command Reference: MARK"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} MARK [OFF]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} OFF/S

 Puts the cursor into mark mode.  As you move the cursor, you will be
 highlighting text for such operations as @{" cut " link Cut} and @{" erase " link Erase}.

  · OFF turns off marking if it was on.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Cut} CUT
   @{"  " link Copy} COPY
   @{"  " link Paste} PASTE
   @{"  " link Erase} ERASE

@endnode

## MATCHBRACKET
##
@node MatchBracket "Command Reference: MATCHBRACKET"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} MATCHBRACKET
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 If the cursor is currently on a bracket, parenthesis, brace, or inequality
 sign, the bracket matching it will be found and jumped to.  This command
 fully handles nested brackets.

@endnode

## MEMORY
##
@node Memory "Command Reference: MEMORY"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} MEMORY
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,
@{b}» FOR ADVANCED USERS ONLY@{ub}

 Presents the @{" Memory " link Memory} requester for setting memory options in
 @{i}Quill@{ui}.

@endnode

## MOVEWINDOW
##
@node MoveWindow "Command Reference: MOVEWINDOW"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} MOVEWINDOW [LEFTEDGE] @{i}<leftedge>@{ui} [TOPEDGE] @{i}<topedge>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} LEFTEDGE/N,TOPEDGE/N

 Changes the position of the current project window.  If the window can't be
 moved as requested, @{i}Quill@{ui} will do the best job possible to move it as you
 request.

  · LEFTEDGE is the new left edge you want.

  · TOPEDGE is the new top edge you want.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link SizeWindow} SIZEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ChangeWindow} CHANGEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ZoomWindow} ZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link UnZoomWindow} UNZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link WindowToFront} WINDOWTOFRONT
   @{"  " link WindowToBack} WINDOWTOBACK
   @{"  " link ScreenToFront} SCREENTOFRONT
   @{"  " link ScreenToBack} SCREENTOBACK

@endnode

## NEW
##
@node New "Command Reference: NEW"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} NEW
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Opens up a new empty editing window infront of the currently active window.
 This allows you to edit multiple files at once.

 There is currently a limit of 10 editor windows that can be open at any
 one time.

@endnode

## NEXTWORD
##
@node NextWord "Command Reference: NEXTWORD"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} NEXTWORD
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Moves the cursor to the start of the next word.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GotoLine} GOTOLINE
   @{"  " link GotoColumn} GOTOCOLUMN
   @{"  " link Cursor} CURSOR
   @{"  " link Line} LINE
   @{"  " link Column} COLUMN
   @{"  " link PreviousWord} PREVIOUSWORD
   @{"  " link Position} POSITION

@endnode

## OPEN
##
@node Open "Command Reference: OPEN"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} OPEN [[FILENAME] @{i}<filename>@{ui}] [FORCE]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FILENAME,FORCE/S

 Opens the specified project into the current editor window, replacing
 whatever text was already there.  If no filename is passed, the user will
 be presented with the file requester for selecting a file.

  · FORCE suppresses the Modified Project requester.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Insert} INSERT

@endnode

## PASTE
##
@node Paste "Command Reference: PASTE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} PASTE
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Takes the text from the standard system clipboard and inserts it into the
 current editor project at the current cursor position.  The data in the
 clipboard may have been @{" cut " link Cut} or @{" copied " link Copy} from any @{i}Quill@{ui} editor window or
 any other application using the standard system clipboard.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Mark} MARK
   @{"  " link Cut} CUT
   @{"  " link Copy} COPY
   @{"  " link Erase} ERASE

@endnode

## POSITION
##
@node Position "Command Reference: POSITION"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} POSITION SOF | EOF | SOL | EOL | SOW | EOW | SOV | EOV | SOS | SOV
 @{b}Template:@{ub} SOF/S,EOF/S,SOL/S,EOL/S,SOW/S,EOW/S,SOV/S,EOV/S,SOS/S,EOS/V

 Moves the cursor to the new position specified.

  · SOF moves it to the beginning of the file.

  · EOF moves it to the end of the file.

  · SOL moves it to the beginning of the line.

  · EOL moves it to the end of the line.

  · SOW moves it to the beginning of the word.

  · EOW moves it to the end of the word.

  · SOV moves it to the beginning of the view, i.e. the far left of the
    screen.  If the cursor is already at the start of the view, the screen
    will be scrolled left.

  · EOV moves it to the end of the view, i.e. the far right of the screen
    If the cursor is already at the end of the view, the screen will be
    scrolled right.

  · SOS moves it to the top of the screen.  If the cursor is already at the
    start of the screen, the screen will be scrolled up.

  · EOS moves it to the bottom of the screen.  If the cursor is already at
    the bottom of the screen, the screen will be scrolled down.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GotoLine} GOTOLINE
   @{"  " link GotoColumn} GOTOCOLUMN
   @{"  " link Cursor} CURSOR
   @{"  " link Line} LINE
   @{"  " link Column} COLUMN
   @{"  " link NextWord} NEXTWORD
   @{"  " link PreviousWord} PREVIOUSWORD

@endnode

## PREVIOUSWORD
##
@node PreviousWord "Command Reference: PREVIOUSWORD"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} PREVIOUSWORD
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Moves the cursor position to the end of the previous word.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GotoLine} GOTOLINE
   @{"  " link GotoColumn} GOTOCOLUMN
   @{"  " link Cursor} CURSOR
   @{"  " link Line} LINE
   @{"  " link Column} COLUMN
   @{"  " link NextWord} NEXTWORD
   @{"  " link Position} POSITION

@endnode

## PRINT
##
@node Print "Command Reference: PRINT"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} PRINT [FORCE]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FORCE/S

 Sends the file in the current editor window to the print "as-is".  Be sure 
 that you have your printer ready and setup as you want it to be via the
 Workbench Printer preferences.

 If a block is current being marked, then only the marked area will be
 printed.

  · FORCE suppresses the confirmation requester.

@endnode

## QUIT
##
@node Quit "Command Reference: QUIT"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} QUIT [FORCE]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FORCE/S

 Exits @{i}Digital Quill@{ui} entirely.  If the project in any of the editor windows
 have not been saved since they were last modified, you will be given a chance
 to @{" save " link SaveAs} them before quitting.

  · FORCE suppresses the Modified Project requester.

@endnode

## REDO
##
@node ReDo "Command Reference: REDO"
@{b}Usage:@{ub} REDO
@{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 If you have @{" undone " link Undo} an edit and decide that you did not in fact want to undo
 it, you can redo that edit with this function.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link UnDo} UNDO

@endnode

## REFORMAT
##
@node Reformat "Command Reference: REFORMAT"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} REFORMAT
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Formats the current paragraph into @{" word-wrapped " link SetAttr} lines that fit within the
 @{" right margin " link SetAttr} setting.  @{i}Quill@{ui} has no hard definition of a paragraph, only of
 a line, so it will attempt to detect the end of the paragraph by looking for
 the following: two consecutive newlines, a newline followed by a space or
 tab, or the end of text.  This should be kept in mind when using this command
 or you might end up with unexpected results.  REFORMAT generally only
 works well with words written in simple paragraph form with no extra
 spacing and indenting for formatting.

@endnode

## REMAKESCREEN
##
@node RemakeScreen "Command Reference: REMAKESCREEN"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} REMAKESCREEN
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Does a complete remake of the @{i}Quill@{ui} display.  All windows and, if open on a
 custom screen, the @{i}Quill@{ui} screen, will be closed down and then re-opened and
 refreshed.

@endnode

## REQUESTFILE
##
@node RequestFile "Command Reference: REQUESTFILE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} REQUESTFILE [TITLE @{i}<title>@{ui}] [PATH @{i}<path>@{ui}] [FILE @{i}<file>@{ui}] [PATH @{i}<path>@{ui}]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} TITLE/K,PATH/K,FILE/K,PATTERN/K

 Brings up a file requester.  You may specify default path and file names.

 The full pathname selected will be returned in RESULT, or a warning level of
 5 in RC if the user cancels the requester.

  · TITLE is what is to appear in the title bar of the file requester.

  · PATH is the default path to appear in the drawer gadget of the file
    requester.  If you don't provide a path then the current directory will
    be used.

  · FILE is the default filename to appear in the file gadget of the file
    requester.

  · PATTERN is the default pattern for matching files to appear in the
    pattern gadget.  If you don't provide a pattern the #? (match all files)
    will be used.  Note that the file requester will always filter out files
    ending in ".info".

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link RequestItem} REQUESTITEM
   @{"  " link RequestString} REQUESTSTRING
   @{"  " link RequestNumber} REQUESTNUMBER
   @{"  " link RequestResponse} REQUESTRESPONSE
   @{"  " link RequestNotify} REQUESTNOTIFY

@endnode

## REQUESTITEM
##
@node RequestItem "Command Reference: REQUESTITEM"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} REQUESTFILE [PROMPT] @{i}<prompt text>@{ui} STEM @{i}<stem>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} PROMPT,STEM/K/A

 Brings up a requester allowing the user to select an item from a list.  The
 list is provide in an ARexx stem variable, with each item in the stem
 @{i}<stemname>@{ui}.# where # is from 0 to n and @{i}<stemname>@{ui}.COUNT is the total number
 of items.

 The index of the item selected is returned in RESULT, or a warning level of
 5 in RC if the user cancels the requester.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link RequestFile} REQUESTFILE
   @{"  " link RequestString} REQUESTSTRING
   @{"  " link RequestNumber} REQUESTNUMBER
   @{"  " link RequestResponse} REQUESTRESPONSE
   @{"  " link RequestNotify} REQUESTNOTIFY

@endnode

## REQUESTNOTIFY
##
@node RequestNotify "Command Reference: REQUESTNOTIFY"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} REQUESTNOTIFY [PROMPT] @{i}<prompt text>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} PROMPT

 Brings up a requester to notify the user of some circumstance.  The
 requester will have a "Continue" gadget for the user to use when he/she is
 ready to continue.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link RequestFile} REQUESTFILE
   @{"  " link RequestItem} REQUESTITEM
   @{"  " link RequestString} REQUESTSTRING
   @{"  " link RequestNumber} REQUESTNUMBER
   @{"  " link RequestResponse} REQUESTRESPONSE

@endnode

## REQUESTNUMBER
##
@node RequestNumber "Command Reference: REQUESTNUMBER"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} REQUESTNUMBER [PROMPT] @{i}<prompt text>@{ui} [DEFAULT @{i}<default value>@{ui}]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} PROMPT,DEFAULT/K

 This command brings up a number entry requester.  You may specify a prompt
 and a default number to be placed in the string editing gadget. 
 Currently only integer values are accepted, floating point values (i.e.
 values witha decimal point) are not allowed.

 The user may enter a value in hexadecimal form by preceeding it with
 "0x", eg. "0x20" for 20 base16, 32 base10.
 
 The number entered will be returned in RESULT, or a warning level of 5 in RC
 if the user cancels the requester.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link RequestFile} REQUESTFILE
   @{"  " link RequestItem} REQUESTITEM
   @{"  " link RequestString} REQUESTSTRING
   @{"  " link RequestResponse} REQUESTRESPONSE
   @{"  " link RequestNotify} REQUESTNOTIFY

@endnode

## REQUESTRESPONSE
##
@node RequestResponse "Command Reference: REQUESTRESPONSE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} REQUESTRESPONSE [PROMPT] @{i}<prompt text>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} PROMPT

 This command brings up a query requester.  You can specify a prompt string
 for which the user may respond to with either "OK" or "Cancel".

 A warning level of 5 will be returned in RC if the user selects cancel.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link RequestFile} REQUESTFILE
   @{"  " link RequestItem} REQUESTITEM
   @{"  " link RequestNotify} REQUESTNOTIFY
   @{"  " link RequestNumber} REQUESTNUMBER
   @{"  " link RequestString} REQUESTSTRING

@endnode

## REQUESTSTRING
##
@node RequestString "Command Reference: REQUESTSTRING"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} REQUESTSTRING [PROMPT] @{i}<prompt text>@{ui} [DEFAULT @{i}<default value>@{ui}]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} "PROMPT,DEFAULT/K

 This command brings up a string entry requester.  You may specify a prompt
 and a default string to be placed in the string editing gadget.
 
 The string entered will be returned in RESULT, or a warning level of 5 in RC
 if the user cancels the requester.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link RequestFile} REQUESTFILE
   @{"  " link RequestNumber} REQUESTNUMBER
   @{"  " link RequestResponse} REQUESTRESPONSE
   @{"  " link RequestNotify} REQUESTNOTIFY

@endnode

## REVEAL
##
@node Reveal "Command Reference: REVEAL, SELECT"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} REVEAL [NAME] @{i}<name>@{ui} | [NUMBER] @{i}<number>@{ui} | NEXT | PREV | TOP | BOTTOM | PROMPT
        SELECT [NAME] @{i}<name>@{ui} | [NUMBER] @{i}<number>@{ui} | NEXT | PREV | TOP | BOTTOM | PROMPT
 @{b}Template:@{ub} NAME,NUMBER/N,NEXT/S,PREV=PREVIOUS/S,TOP/S,BOTTOM/S,PROMPT/S

 Selects a project to be the currently active one.

  · NAME is the name of the project you want to make active.  If this is not
    a project @{i}Quill@{ui} already has open then @{i}Quill@{ui} will try to load it from
    disk.

  · NUMBER specifies a project number of the project you want to make active.
  
  · NEXT selects the next project after the current one to be active, or the
    first project if the last one is currently active.

  · PREV selects the next project before the current one to be active, or the
    last project if the first one is currently active.

  · TOP selects the last project to be active.

  · BOTTOM selects the first project to be active.

  · PROMPT offers the user a list of all projects for her/him to select from.

@endnode

## RX
##
@node Rx "Command Reference: RX"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} RX [COMMAND] @{i}<command>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} COMMAND/F

 Starts an ARexx macro.  All macros are executed asynchronously and will
 inherit Quill's output stream.

  · COMMAND is the name of the macro you want to execute.  If not given,
    the user will be prompted with the file requester.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link RxS} RXS

@endnode

## RXS
##
@node RxS "Command Reference: RXS"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} RXS [STRING] @{i}<command>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} STRING/F

 Sends a string command to ARexx.  The command will be given an output
 console if needed automatically.

  · STRING is the command you want to send to ARexx.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link Rx} RX

@endnode

## SAVE
##
@node Save "Command Reference: SAVE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SAVE [FORCE]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FORCE/S

 Saves the file in the current editor window to disk, using the current project
 name.  If no name has been specified yet, you'll be able to select a name
 using the file requester.

 If a block is current being marked, then only the marked area will be
 saved.

  · FORCE suppresses any confirmation requesters.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link SaveAs} SAVEAS

@endnode

## SAVEAS
##
@node SaveAs "Command Reference: SAVEAS"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SAVEAS [[FILENAME] @{i}<filename>@{ui}] [FORCE]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FILENAME,FORCE/S

 Saves the current project to the specified filename.  If no filename is
 passed, the user will be presented with the file requester for selecting a
 file.

 If a block is current being marked, then only the marked area will be
 saved.

  · FILENAME specifies the new name for the project.  If no name is given
    then the file requester will appear so that a name can be given.

  · FORCE suppresses any confirmation requesters.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link SAVE} SAVE

@endnode

## SAVESETTINGS
##
@node SaveSettings "Command Reference: SAVESETTINGS"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SAVESETTINGS
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Saves the Digital Quill settings to disk.

 The settings consist of all parameters set via the @{" Settings " link Menus} pull-down menu,
 and in addition: the current window position and size, the current directory,
 the current file requester pattern, etc.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link LoadSettings} LOADSETTINGS
   @{"  " link SaveSettingsAs} SAVESETTINGSAS

@endnode

## SAVESETTINGSAS
##
@node SaveSettingsAs "Command Reference: SAVESETTINGSAS"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SAVESETTINGSAS [[FILENAME] @{i}<filename>@{ui}]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} FILENAME

 Save the @{i}Digital Quill@{ui} settings to a file.  If no file is specified, the
 user will be presented with the file requester for selecting a file.

 The settings consist of all parameters set via the @{" Settings " link Menus} pull-down menu,
 and in addition: the current window position and size, the current directory,
 the current file requester pattern, etc.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link LoadSettings} LOADSETTINGS
   @{"  " link SaveSettings} SAVESETTINGS

@endnode

## SCREENTOBACK
##
@node ScreenToBack "Command Reference: SCREENTOBACK"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SCREENTOBACK
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Puts the @{i}Quill@{ui} screen behind all other screens.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link MoveWindow} MOVEWINDOW
   @{"  " link SizeWindow} SIZEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ChangeWindow} CHANGEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ZoomWindow} ZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link UnZoomWindow} UNZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link WindowToFront} WINDOWTOFRONT
   @{"  " link WindowToBack} WINDOWTOBACK
   @{"  " link ScreenToFront} SCREENTOFRONT

@endnode

## SCREENTOFRONT
##
@node ScreenToFront "Command Reference: SCREENTOFRONT"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SCREENTOFRONT
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Makes the @{i}Quill@{ui} screen to the frontmost screen

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link MoveWindow} MOVEWINDOW
   @{"  " link SizeWindow} SIZEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ChangeWindow} CHANGEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ZoomWindow} ZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link UnZoomWindow} UNZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link WindowToFront} WINDOWTOFRONT
   @{"  " link WindowToBack} WINDOWTOBACK
   @{"  " link ScreenToBack} SCREENTOBACK

@endnode

## SETATTR
##
@node SetAttr "Command Reference: SETATTR"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SETATTR [OBJECT] @{i}<object>@{ui} [[FIELD1] @{i}<field1>@{ui}] [[FIELD2] @{i}<field2>@{ui}]
        [[VALUE] @{i}<value>@{ui}] [[VAR] @{i}<var>@{ui}]
 @{b}Template:@{ub} OBJECT/A,FIELD1,FIELD2,VALUE/K,VAR/K

 Allows you to set an attribute within Quill.  Attributes are hierarchical,
 and currently you can only change one attribute at a time, thus you must
 specify the full hierarchy of the attribute.

  · OBJECT can be used to set attributes from any of the following:
     · PROJECT      - @{i}See fields for the PROJECT object below.@{ui}

  · FIELD1 allows you to set a field of information from an @{i}object@{ui}.

    With the PROJECT object, @{i}field1@{ui} can be used to get the following
    attributes:
     · SAVETABS     - (Boolean)
     · CREATEICONS  - (Boolean)
     · BACKUPTIME   - (Integer)
     · FILENAME     - (String)
     · PATH         - (String)
     · FILE         - (String)
     · EDITING      - @{i}See sub-fields for EDITING below.@{ui}
     · ENVIRONMENT  - @{i}See sub-fields for ENVIRONEMENT below.@{ui}

  · FIELD2 allows you to get a more specific field of information from a
    @{i}field@{ui} within an @{i}object@{ui}.

    From the field1 EDITING in the PROJECT object, the sub-field @{i}field2@{ui} can
    be any of:
     · INSERT       - (Boolean)
     · WORDWRAP     - (Boolean)
     · AUTOINDENT   - (Boolean)
     · FALSETABS    - (Boolean)
     · TABSIZE      - (Integer)
     · RIGHTMARGIN  - (Integer)

    From the field1 ENVIRONMENT in the PROJECT object, the sub-field @{i}field2@{ui} can
    be any of:
     · FREECURSOR   - (Boolean)
     · DRAGMARK     - (Boolean)
     · FENCEPOSTING - (Boolean)
     · SHOWHEX      - (Boolean)
     · SPEEDBAR     - (Boolean)
     · LARGEBUTTONS - (Boolean)

 Boolean attributes you can set to either ON or OFF, or you can specify
 TOGGLE to toggle their current state.

 Integer attributes you can pass a numberic value for, or if you don't pass a
 value a numeric requester will appear for the user to type a value in that
 will become the new value for the attribute.

 @{b}Examples:@{ub}
   To make sure insert mode is on:
     SETATTR PROJECT EDITING INSERT ON

   To toggle fence-posting:
     SETATTR PROJECT ENVIRONMENT FENCEPOSTING TOGGLE

   To change the tab size to 8:
     SETATTR PROJECT ENVIRONMENT TABSIZE 8

   To allow the user to enter a new right margin value:
     SETATTR PROJECT ENVIRONMENT RIGHTMARGIN

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GetAttr} GETATTR

@endnode

## SETBOOKMARK
##
@node SetBookMark "Command Reference: SETBOOKMARK"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SETBOOKMARK
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Places a bookmark at the current cursor position.  This means that the
 position of the bookmark will be remembered so that it can quickly be
 jumped to later with either the @{" GOTOBOOKMARK " link GotoBookMark} or @{" SWAPBOOKMARK " link SwapBookMark} commands.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link GotoBookMark} GOTOBOOKMARK
   @{"  " link SwapBookMark} SWAPBOOKMARK

@endnode

## SETSTATUSBAR
##
@node SetStatusBar "Command Reference: SETSTATUSBAR"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SETSTATUSBAR [TEXT] @{i}<text>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} TEXT/F

 Sets a status message.  Status messages in @{i}Quill@{ui} appear in the title bar.
 A status message is only temporary and will be cleared by any subsequent
 action the user makes.

@endnode

## SIZEWINDOW
##
@node SizeWindow "Command Reference: SIZEWINDOW"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SIZEWINDOW [WIDTH] @{i}<width>@{ui} [HEIGHT] @{i}<height>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} WIDTH/N,HEIGHT/N

 Changes the size of the current project window to the given width and
 height.

 · WIDTH specifies the new width for the window.

 · HEIGHT specifies the new height for the window.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link MoveWindow} MOVEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ChangeWindow} CHANGEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ZoomWindow} ZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link UnZoomWindow} UNZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link WindowToFront} WINDOWTOFRONT
   @{"  " link WindowToBack} WINDOWTOBACK
   @{"  " link ScreenToFront} SCREENTOFRONT
   @{"  " link ScreenToBack} SCREENTOBACK

@endnode

## SWAPBOOKMARK
##
@node SwapBookMark "Command Reference: SWAPBOOKMARK"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SWAPBOOKMARK
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Jumps to the @{" bookmark " link SetBookMark}, making the old cursor position the new bookmark.
 This can be used to quickly toggle back and forth between two spots in a
 project.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link SetBookMark} SETBOOKMARK
   @{"  " link GotoBookMark} GOTOBOOKMARK

@endnode

## SYSTEM
##
@node System "Command Reference: SYSTEM"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} SYSTEM [ASYNC] [PUBSCREEN] [HOSTPORT] [COMMAND] @{i}<command>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ASYNC/S,PUBSCREEN/S,HOSTPORT/S,COMMAND/F

 Executes an AmigaDOS command.

  · ASYNC specifies that the command be run asynchronously and that control
    be immediately returned to @{i}Quill@{ui}.

  · PUBSCREEN causes the name of the screen @{i}Quill@{ui} is running on to be
    included in the command string with the PUBSCREEN keyword.  Use this to
    get other programmes to open on the same screen as @{i}Quill@{ui}.

  · HOSTPORT causes the name of the ARexx port @{i}Quill@{ui} is using to be
    included in the command string with the HOSTPORT keyword.  Use this to
    pass @{i}Quill's@{ui} ARexx port to another programme for that programme
    to communicate with @{i}Quill@{ui}.

  · COMMAND is the AmigaDOS command to run.  Standard redirection with < and
    > is supported.

@endnode

## TEXT
##
@node Text "Command Reference: TEXT"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} TEXT [TEXT] @{i}<text>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} TEXT/F

 Inserts text into the current project window at the current cursor postion.

@endnode

## TEXTPEN
##
@node TextPen "Command Reference: TEXTPEN"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} TEXTPEN @{i}<pen number>@{ui}
 @{b}Template:@{ub} /N

 Changes the colour of the text pen in all project windows to the given pen
 number.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link BackgroundPen} BACKGROUNDPEN

@endnode

## UNDO
##
@node UnDo "Command Reference: UNDO"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} UNDO
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Reverses the last edit made.  Anything that changes the current project,
 entering text, deleting text, doing a @{" find and replace " link FindChange}, @{" pasting " link Paste} from the
 clipboard, @{" erasing a block " link Erase}, etc. can all be undone.  You can undo for
 numerous levels, the limits of which are defined in the @{" Memory " link Memory} requester.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link ReDo} REDO

@endnode

## UNLOCKGUI
##
@node UnlockGUI "Command Reference: UNLOCKGUI"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} UNLOCKGUI
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Unlocks @{i}Quill's@{ui} graphic user interface if it had been previously @{" locked " link LockGUI}.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link LockGUI} LOCKGUI

@endnode

## UNZOOMWINDOW
##
@node UnZoomWindow "Command Reference: UNZOOMWINDOW"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} UNZOOMWINDOW
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 If the current project window is zoomed this command will unzoom it,
 equivalent to clicking on the zoom gadget in the project window while the
 window is in its zoomed state.
 
 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link MoveWindow} MOVEWINDOW
   @{"  " link SizeWindow} SIZEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ChangeWindow} CHANGEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ZoomWindow} ZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link WindowToFront} WINDOWTOFRONT
   @{"  " link WindowToBack} WINDOWTOBACK
   @{"  " link ScreenToFront} SCREENTOFRONT
   @{"  " link ScreenToBack} SCREENTOBACK

@endnode

## UPPERCASE
##
@node UpperCase "Command Reference: UPPERCASE"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} UPPERCASE
 @{b}Template:@{ub} CHAR/S,WORD/S,LINE/S

 Converts from the cursor position to the end of the word to all uppercase
 letters, regardless of what case they were before.  Or, if an area is being
 @{" marked " link Mark}, that entire area will be converted to all uppercase.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link LowerCase} LOWERCASE

@endnode

## WINDOWTOBACK
##
@node WindowToBack "Command Reference: WINDOWTOBACK"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} WINDOWTOBACK
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Moves the current project window behind all others.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link MoveWindow} MOVEWINDOW
   @{"  " link SizeWindow} SIZEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ChangeWindow} CHANGEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ZoomWindow} ZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link UnZoomWindow} UNZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link WindowToFront} WINDOWTOFRONT
   @{"  " link ScreenToFront} SCREENTOFRONT
   @{"  " link ScreenToBack} SCREENTOBACK

@endnode

## WINDOWTOFRONT
##
@node WindowToFront "Command Reference: WINDOWTOFRONT"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} WINDOWTOFRONT
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Brings the current project window to the front.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link MoveWindow} MOVEWINDOW
   @{"  " link SizeWindow} SIZEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ChangeWindow} CHANGEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ZoomWindow} ZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link UnZoomWindow} UNZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link WindowToBack} WINDOWTOBACK
   @{"  " link ScreenToFront} SCREENTOFRONT
   @{"  " link ScreenToBack} SCREENTOBACK

@endnode

## ZOOMWINDOW
##
@node ZoomWindow "Command Reference: ZOOMWINDOW"
 @{b}Usage:@{ub} ZOOMWINDOW
 @{b}Template:@{ub} ,

 Zooms the current project window to the alternate zoom size.  Equivalent to
 clicking on the zoom gadget in the project window while the window is in its
 unzoomed state.

 @{b}See Also:@{ub}
   @{"  " link MoveWindow} MOVEWINDOW
   @{"  " link SizeWindow} SIZEWINDOW
   @{"  " link ChangeWindow} CHANGEWINDOW
   @{"  " link UnZoomWindow} UNZOOMWINDOW
   @{"  " link WindowToFront} WINDOWTOFRONT
   @{"  " link WindowToBack} WINDOWTOBACK
   @{"  " link ScreenToFront} SCREENTOFRONT
   @{"  " link ScreenToBack} SCREENTOBACK

@endnode

